==Old English==
===Spellings===
wæsp, wæps, wæfs

===Etymology===
From West Germanic ''*wepsō-'', from Indo-European ''*wobhsā-'' ‘wasp’, from ''*webh-'' ‘weave’ (referring to the insect's woven nests).  Germanic cognates include Old Saxon [[waspa]], [[wepsia]] (Dutch [[wesp]]), Old High German [[wefsa]] (German [[Wespe]]).  The IE root is also the source of Avestan ''vawžaka-'', Old Breton [[guohi]], Latin [[vespa]] (Italian [[vespa]]), Lithuanian [[vapsa|vapsà]], Russian [[оса]].  The word is also related to English [[web]] and [[weave]].

